at|^*B
Super-Accepting in its simplest and easiest to remember form is:
When you open 1NT with a 4+ card in one of the majors,
partner transfers to that major, and finally
you have an exemplary or beautiful 1NT hand. ^*N|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

So, playing standard Super-Accept, you bid 3@H when partner is transferring to hearts (he bids 2@D). Or you bid 3@S after a 2@H transfer to spades. With those information your partner re-evaluates his hand and makes the appropriate bid--pass, bid game or etc. What we really need to learn is what makes a 1NT hand ^*IExemplary, or Beautiful or Super^*N.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


AT|

Howard our teacher and mentor, has the following simple guideline. 

"After a strong 1N opening 15/17, I always play Super-Accept with four-card support unless I have the ^*Bflattest 15 point NT^*N opening. Marty Bergen is a strong proponent of this method. It is based on the Law of Total Tricks, as you can bid to three level with nine card fit. However, many experts play the more restrictive Super-Accepts-4 trumps and 16/17 points Notrump. That is something that partnerships should discuss and agree on."|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


at|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NWithout any question then, having 4+ card in the transferred suit is a must for considering a Super-Accept. However, the qualities which make a Notrump hand exemplary and worthy for a Super-Accept are the source of many debates and the base for many modifications.|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


AT|

According to Howard, the ^*Bflattest 15 HCP NT^*N hand cannot be exemplary enough for a Super-Accept. That is really all we need to play standard Super-Accept and have good results more often than not. However, Movie Maker would be out of his day job if you do not insist on knowing all about the controversies and the modifications.|
