^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|In Standard, notrumper jumps to 3 of the major to Super-Accept--3@H or 3@S. However, when I Super-Accept, I try to give partner extra information. Every time we transfer to a major after a 1NT opening, if opener merely completes the transfer at the two-level, we can be sure the notrumper lacks four trumps. Not only can this prove vital to responder in deciding whether to try for game, but it can also be critical in evaluating slam possibilities. Next is the schedule of rebids for opener after 1NT-P-2@H-?.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


AT|

2@S ^c= two or three spades, any strength hand
2NT ^C= four spades, 4-3-3-3, maximum 1NT hand
3@C ^C= four or more spades, doubleton club, maximum 1NT hand
3@D ^C= four or more spades, doubleton diamond, maximum 1NT hand
3@H ^C= four or more spades, doubleton heart, maximum 1NT hand 
3@S ^C= four or more spades, non-maximum.

Obviously, the same principles apply after 1NT-P-2@D. In this sequence, after a Super-Accept, 3@D "re-transfers" to 3@H. Now, responder can pass, raise to 4@H, or try for slam.|
