^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Here is my simple version:

1) If you open 1NT, and partner bids a 2@D/2@H Jacoby transfer, always jump to 3@H/3@S with 4-card support regardless of HCP.

2) If you open 2NT (or rebid 2NT after a 2@C opener), and partner bids a 3@D/3@H Jacoby transfer, jump to 4@H/4@S with 4-card support.

Marty Bergen has a more complicated set of rules, but he essentially agrees with the above. 

As long as we are on the subject of transfers, here is some bonus material for you. When partner's transfer bid is doubled (lead directing), the NT bidder's responses are as follows:

1) With 2-card support pass. The transfer bidder can then redouble to re-transfer, or make any other appropriate bid (usually 2NT or 3NT).

2) With 3-card support, immediately accept the transfer (e.g.. bid 2@H/2@S over the 2@D/2@H transfer).

3) With 4-card support, Super-Accept.|
